==Chinese==

===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
Originally a {{liushu|p|nocap=y}}: a cross-shaped measuring compass similar to {{zh-l|*乂}}. The protoform also appears as the bottom component in the oracle bone script of {{och-l|*畫}}.

Later reformulated as {{Han compound|夫|見|t1=husband|t2=see|nocap=yes}}, which is traditionally considered an {{liushu|ic|nocap=y}}. However, {{zh-ref|Smith (2011)}} proposes that the left component is an abbreviation of the phonetic component {{och-l|癸}}. Compare the [[癸#Glyph_origin|''Shizhoupian'' script form]] of {{lang|zh|癸}}.

Chen (2021) instead suggests that the {{lang|zh|夫}} is the left-hand side of {{och-l|*矩}}, after {{och-l|*矩}} became seen as a compound; since both characters refer to tools, it would be natural for their semantic components to align.<ref>[https://www.fdgwz.org.cn/Web/Show/7845 陳劍：說“規”等字並論一些特別的形聲字意符]</ref>

